    <name>
				<text>35.4.4.4 Independent vs. mutually exclusive events</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_exercise"> Exercise </h4>
<p> If \(A\) and \(B\) are two events associated with an experiment and \(\displaystyle{\mathbb{P}(A) = {@pa@}}\), \(\displaystyle{\mathbb{P}(A\cup B) = {@pab@}}\) and \(\displaystyle{\mathbb{P}(B) = p}\), find:</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> the choice of \(p\) for which \(A\) and \(B\) are mutually exclusive; </li>
<li> the choice of \(p\) for which \(A\) and \(B\) are independent. </li>
</ol>
<p> Give these probabilities as fractions, rather than decimals: </p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> For mutually exclusive events \(A\) and \(B\), we have \(p=\quad\)[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]] </li>
<li> For independent events \(A\) and \(B\), we have \(p=\quad\)[[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]] </li></ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution"> Solution </h4>
<p> For events \(A\) and \(B\) we have\[\mathbb{P}(A\cup B) = \mathbb{P}(A) + \mathbb{P}(B) - \mathbb{P}(A\cap B). \]</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li> If \(A\) and \(B\) are mutually exclusive then \(\mathbb{P}(A\cap B) = 0\) and therefore\[\mathbb{P}(A\cup B) = \mathbb{P}(A) + \mathbb{P}(B) \]which rearranges to give \(p = \displaystyle {@ta1@}.\)</li>
<li> If \(A\) and \(B\) are independent then \(\mathbb{P}(A\cap B) = \mathbb{P}(A)\mathbb{P}(B)\) so that\[\mathbb{P}(A\cup B) = \mathbb{P}(A) + \mathbb{P}(B) - \mathbb{P}(A)\mathbb{P}(B)\]which rearranges to give \(p =\displaystyle&nbsp; {@ta2@}.\)</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
